# Intuition
One can observe that the elements of the array can be increased/decreased by $k$ any number of times. We use the modular arithmetic approach to set the value to the elements to maximise the $MEX$.

# Approach
Calculate the mod value of every element by $k$ and store it in a hashmap. After that, start from $0$ till $k$, once you reach k start again from $k$ every time you find the mod value can be done reduce the count in map, once you find there is no remainder value to make that number, that becomes the $MEX$. Check example: 

A=$[1,2,3,4,20,6,15]$ k=$4$
$hash_0$=1 (4,20)
$hash_1$=1 (1)
$hash_2$=2 (2,6)
$hash_3$=2 (3,15)

For $0$, there is a hash decrease the count, for $1$, $2$, $3$ there is a hash value decrease the count. 
Once again start from $0$ (this time $MEX$ is 4) there is a hash, but for 1($MEX$ is $5$ here) $hash_1$=0, which becomes the maximum $MEX$ of the array.

The array is internally can be modified like this, A=$[0,1,2,3,4,6,7]$

*Note: To handle the mod of negative value, I added ($k*1e8$)+$v_i$ to obtain the positive mod value as MEX refers to smallest positive integer not present in the array.*

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O($n$) + O($n$) as we are making only $2$ passes.

- Space complexity:
O($k$) hashmap to store the count of mods.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findSmallestInteger(vector<int>& v, int val) {
        vector<int>p(val);
        for(int i=0;i<v.size();i++){
            long long int t=v[i]+(1e8*val);
            p[t%val]++;
        }
        int ct=0;
        while(1){    
            for(int i=0;i<val;i++){
                if(p[i]==0){return ct;}
                ct++;
                p[i]--;
            }
        }
        return 0;
    }
};

```

