# Intuition
First, finding modulo for each number. If modulo is negative, then just add value and we'll get positive number.

Sort the array. We will have arrays of remainders.

Then depending on number of remainders we need to form numbers which give current remainder starting from the remainder itself. Example:
[0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1] with value = 3 will be [0, 3, 6, 1, 4, 7]

After that again sort the array: [0, 1, 3, 4, 6, 7]

And, finally, find the smallest non-existing number from array. [which is 2]

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(3N + 2N*logN) => O(N * (3 + 2logN))


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findSmallestInteger(int[] nums, int value) {
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int n = nums[i];
            int mod = n % value;
            if (mod < 0) mod += value;
            nums[i] = mod;
        }

        Arrays.sort(nums);
        int mem = -1, count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int curr = nums[i];
            if (curr != mem) {
                count = 0;
                mem = curr;
            } else {
                count++;
            }
            nums[i] = curr + count * value;
        }

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        count = 0;
        for (int n : nums) if (n != count++) return count - 1;
        return count;
    }
}
```

