# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Find all mods with their frequency, if a mod has one frequency, it can be used to only create the same number. If a mod has more than one frequency then it can create the same number as well as same number plus value.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Find mod using hash, store frequency. Use frequency to find all possible integers that can be created.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findSmallestInteger(vector<int>& nums, int value) {
        map<int, int> m;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); ++i){
            int currMod = nums[i] % value;
            if(currMod < 0) currMod = (currMod + value) % value;
            m[currMod]++;
        }
        map<int, int> v;
        for(int i = 0; i < value; ++i){
            if(m.find(i) == m.end())
                return i;
            int count = 0;
            while(m[i]-- > 0){
                v[value * count++ + i]++;
            }
        }
        for(int i = 0; i < 1e9; ++i)    if(v.find(i) == v.end())    return i;
        return value;
    }
};
```

