class Solution {
public:
    int findSmallestInteger(vector<int>& nums, int value) {
        unordered_map<int,int>mp;vector<int>values_adding;
        for(auto &num:nums){num%=value;if(num<0)num+=value;mp[num]++;}
        for(auto &freq:mp){
            auto curr=freq.first;
            while(freq.second>1){
                freq.second--;curr+=value;
                values_adding.push_back(curr);
            }
        }for(auto &val:values_adding)mp[val]++;
        for(int i=0;i<1e5+3;i++)if(mp.count(i)==0)return i;return -1;
    }
};
```
note: some knowledge of set theory is required and same for modulo operation 
**logik:**
1. when we take modulo of a number x by value x%value=(a) here a always lies between 0 to value-1 
2. when the modulo is negative like taking -10%3 gives -1 but to make it positive we add value to it again so -10%3 becomes 2 instead of -1
3. now first we take modulo of each element in the given array and make a count of each remainder that occurs in a map
4. now for each number [i]  in the map let the frequency be x[i], while x[i]>1 we will keep adding value to [i]  and storing the result to be added in map (because a,a+value,a+2 x value... ) all can be taken, as any number of operations is possible. So by using this method we eliminate all possibility of picking a MEX value that may be present in array if adding is performed (lets say)k times 
5. now we add all the values in the map, the total empty spaces can be maximum 1e5 (given) but values will be from -(1e9) to (1e9) now, there will always be a value from 0 to 1e5 that is missing and if all values from 0 to 1e5 are present 1e5+1 will be the missing value 
6. hence run a loop from 0 to 1e5+2 to find the missing value in the map, the missing value is the answer
