# Intuition

So, we need mostly positive numbers. if a num % value = x, we can change num to x, x* value, x * value * 2 . Example (6 = 1 in mod 5)

# Approach
1. Find all positive mods in a greedy way. if num % value = x, and x is already found, for example 6 = 1 (mod 5) and 11 = 1 (mod 5) you can extend the next one.
2. Now that we have all values [0,1,2,3,4,5,7,8] (for example), we need to zero in on 6.
3. Note that for any non-gap progression, arr[i] = i, so we can use this to binary search on result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n) + O(len(nums) * log2(len(nums)))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
```
func findSmallestInteger(nums []int, value int) int {
    modSet := make(map[int]bool)
    multiplier := make(map[int]int)
    // remember 6=1 mod 5 if you have more than 1, you can extend them!!
    for _, num := range nums {
        cmod := ((num % value) + value) % value
        _, ok := modSet[cmod]
        if !ok {
            modSet[cmod] = true
            multiplier[cmod] = 0
        } else {
            lastMult, ok := multiplier[cmod]
            if !ok {
                panic("multiplier not found")
            }
            lastMult++
            modSet[lastMult * value + cmod] = true
            multiplier[cmod] = lastMult
        }
    }
    modArr := make([]int, 0)
    for k, _ := range modSet {
        modArr = append(modArr, k)
    }
    sort.Ints(modArr)
    low := 0
    high := len(modArr) - 1
    validMid := -1
    for low <= high {
        mid := low + (high - low)/2
        if modArr[mid] > mid {
            high = mid-1
        } else {
            low = mid+1
            validMid = mid
        }
    }
    if validMid == -1 {
        return 0
    }
    return modArr[validMid]+1
}
```

